And then the idea to then add the NFT to kind of represent that and make it transferable, right, I think is an interesting addition to this, but it allows anybody can still do this after that initial window. So hopefully you cut down on spam. Worst case, these activities still take place and there is a competitive chance for anyone to do it, but it's just pushed back a few blocks. Where I think this gets really cool is what if you actually apply a Harburger tax, a Harbitra tax to this. So the idea here for those who aren't familiar is that the owner of the PRT gets to set a price for the PRT and they're paying a tax on the basis of that price. But the other piece of that is that anybody can then buy the PRT off them for that price. So it's in their best interest to price it at what they think is like a fair value that they're willing to pay. And they can still be profitable because they try to underprice it, somebody else will grab it. If they overprice it, they're paying more in tax than the opportunity is really worth to them. And so the result here should be that the PRT ends up in the most efficient hands to hold it. And the assumption here is that that would end up being roughly equal to what is currently being expended in total on gas or other costs for back running transactions in a competitive manner.
